          "Blended Learning",
          "Dropout",
          "At-risk (1) vs Not at-risk (0)",
          "141 students",
          "Not Specified",
          "SIS, LMS logs, Survey",
          "[Age, Gender, Ethnicity, Postcode location (deprivation level proxy), Campus of study, Mode of study (full-time / part-time), Entry qualification, Disability status, Total login time, Number of resources viewed, Number of module quiz attempts submitted, Number of module forum course views, Number of module forum discussion reads/views, Parent economic status, Work hours, Work pressure, Entry qualification (self-reported context variable), Average study hours, Family support, Course satisfaction, Technology impact, Learning style, Health status, First in university (first-generation student), Adaptation (adjustment to university), University support, Prior course knowledge]",
          "End of Semester",
          "Authors test different configurations of features: \n\nData from SIS alone, LMS alone, Survey Alone and combinations of different data sources.\n\nBanner data includes 8 features, LMS 5 and Survey includes 14 features\n\nHyperparameter tuning is achieved using 10-Fold CV",
          "MLP, SVM, DT, Stacking",
          "Holdout Method (70/30)",
          "{Accuracy: 0.8295 - SVM - Survey, RMSE: 0.396 - Stacking - All Sources, Precision: 0.7962- Stacking - All Sources, Recall: 0.7586 - Stacking - All Sources, F1-Score: 0.7769 - Stacking - All Sources}",
          "This study investigates whether combining multiple data sources and heterogeneous ensemble methods improves the prediction of student academic performance. Using data from 141 students at the University of the West of Scotland, the authors integrate demographic (SRS), behavioral (LMS), and psychological/survey variables. They compare decision tree, neural network, and support vector machine classifiers against a stacking ensemble approach. The hybrid ensemble model that combines all three data sources achieves the highest predictive performance (around 81% accuracy). The authors conclude that multi-source ensemble modeling can support early identification of students at risk of poor performance and potential attrition.",
          "Unclear operational definition of performance\n\nTemporal ambiguity\n\nSmall sample size\n\nSingle-institution context\n\nLimited transparency on course scope\n\nNo early prediction"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
